8e0467c2-e163-4ea0-bf92-e5c5fe7d6f73	Controlling other machine remotely	So I had to connect to my friend's linux terminal (yeah we're becoming linux-neovim coders). From last 3 days, we were using anydesk. Then i remembered about ssh. Normally we connect to other devices on ssh by:\n1. If we're connected on same network: ssh username-of-friend@hisLocalIpAddress\n2. If we're far then: ssh username-of-friend@hisPublicIpAddress\n\nSecond way is good, but we need port forwarding too, which many router don't support. So I found out about tailscale, a tool which creates a private peer to peer connection between two users, and gives a private ip address for both, so we could connect using: ssh username-of-friend@hisTailscaleIpAddress and done.\n\nNow another issue, how do we share the same screen, like whatever he'll do, i won't be able to see, and vice versa. Ubuntu has an inbuilt tool called tmux, u can create multiple terminal sessions on it, can detach from it and attach to it without actually killing that session, so if we both connect to same session, we'd be sharing our screen, and done! I practiced this a lot by running a Debian virtualbox, running tailscale inside it, and SSHing into that virtual machine from my WSL, brainfuck level of inception lol, three linux machines on single pc.\n\nanother way is to use tmate, but it's kinda slow and knowing ssh etc stuffs is good for multiple purposes.	f	2025-04-13 13:43:43.333+00	2025-04-14 17:18:00.007+00	61e5569a-8633-40f1-8f4f-8b2e60c8c036
